THE VIDEOGRAPHER:  Good morning Here begins videotape No. l in the 
deposition of Allen Cowlings, Volume III, in the consolidated cases of Fredric 
Goldman, Sharon Rufo and Louis Brown vs. Orenthal James Simpson in the 
Superior Court, State of California, County of Los Angeles, the lead case 
number of which is SC 031947. Today's date is April 26, 1996.  The time is 
approximately 9:58.  This deposition is being taken at 11377 West Olympic 
Boulevard in Los Angeles, California, and was made at the request of plaintiff 
of the Law Offices of Mitchell, Silberberg & Knupp.   
 
The videographer is Rod Rigole, employed by Coleman, Haas, Martin & 
Schwab of Los Angeles, California. 
 
Would counsel please identify yourselves and state whom you represent. 
 
MR. KELLY:  John Kelly for the Estate of Nicole Brown Simpson. 
 
MR. BREWER: Michael Brewer for Plaintiff Sharon Rufo. 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Daniel Petrocelli for Plaintiff Fredric Goldman. 
 
MR. LEONARD: Daniel Leonard for O.J. Simpson. 
 
MR. RE: Donald Re for Allen Cowlings. 
 
 
ALLEN COWLINGS, having been first duly sworn, was examined and testified 
further as follows: 
 
EXAMINATION (Resumed)  
 
BY MR. KELLY: Good morning, Mr. Cowlings.  
 
A: Morning. 
 
Q: How you doing? 
 
A: Fine. 
 
Q: Good. Mr. Cowlings, have you spoken to anybody since last Wednesday 
when you left here regarding the testimony you have given us to date? 
 
A: No. Except my lawyer. 
 
Q: Other than Mr. Re, have you spoken to anybody? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Have you spoken to Mr. Simpson since last Wednesday -- 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: -- when you left here? I'm sorry? 
 
A: No. 
 
MR. RE: I should make it clear, I have asked him not to speak to Mr. Simpson -- 
 
MR. KELLY: Okay. 
 
MR. RE: -- during the pendency of this deposition. 
 
MR. KELLY: Okay, great. 
 
Q: And you recall that you have asserted what we have referred to as the 
privilege a number of  times the last couple days when asked questions? 
 
A: Pertaining to 
 
Q: Certain events. 
 
A: Certain dates. 
 
Q: Certain dates? 
 
A: (Nods head.) 
 
Q: Yes. And would you be willing to testify fully regarding those dates if given 
immunity by the District Attorney's Office? 
 
MR. RE: I don't think he would have any choice. The only quarrel I have is 
when you say, "immunity by the District Attorney's Office," you mean given 
immunity -- 
 
MR. KELLY: From criminal prosecution. 
 
MR. RE: Theoretically, the immunity would come from the court as opposed to 
the District Attorney's Office. 
 
MR. KELLY: Right. 
 
MR. RE: Okay. 
 
THE WITNESS: Yes. 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
 
Q: Okay. How long have you known Robert Kardashian, Mr. Cowlings? 
 
A: Quite a long time. I think we met in the early '70s. 
 
Q: And where did you meet him? 
 
A: I actually met Bob through O.J., met Bob and his brother. All of us just 
started -- well, myself, I had just started playing tennis, and they were very nice 
to invite us over to play tennis with them. 
 
Q: What's Bob's brother's name? 
 
A: Tom. Tom Kardashian. 
 
Q: And you used to spend a lot of time at the Kardashian's place? 
 
A: Yeah, there, and we would frequent -- we would go out to dinner, you know. 
Great family. 
 
Q: Okay. And what about his first wife Chris, did you know her? 
 
A: Yes, knew Chris well. 
 
Q: And when did you first meet her? 
 
A: I guess when her and Bob started dating. 
 
Q: Okay. Do you recall approximately what year that was? 
 
A: Still in the '70s, probably mid '70s, I would think. I don't know for sure. She 
was an airline stewardess when they met, and I helped her move, too, eventually 
when she moved out of her apartment in the Valley. 
 
Q: Okay. When you first met Bob Kardashian, do you know what type of 
employment he was involved in, what his profession was? 
 
A: I think he was a lawyer. 
 
Q: Okay. Did he ever do any legal work or provide any legal services on your 
behalf? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Okay. And when you met him in the early `70s, you indicated you met him 
through Mr. Simpson? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: And do you know what Mr. Simpson's relationship was with Bob Kardashian 
back then? 
 
MR LEONARD: Objection.  Lack of foundation, calls for speculation. 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
 
Q: Other than that, you can answer. 
 
A: Bob, as when I met Bob, turned out that he went to USC, too, and he had 
been the head manager of the football team, which the head manager is like an 
assistant to the coach, to the head coach -- 
 
Q: That was while he was still a student there? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Okay. 
 
A: So the connection is USC, and by the fact of O.J. being very successful there 
and being a Heisman Trophy winner, I guess when Bob -- and I don't know 
exactly where they met, but that was the common denominator for them. 
 
Q: But when you met Kardashian in a social -- You met him in a social setting. 
Is that correct? 
 
A: Yeah. 
 
Q: Okay. And did you used to socialize with both Kardashian and Simpson? 
 
A: At times, yes. 
 
Q: Okay. Did you ever even see a business card for Mr. Kardashian? 
 
A: I don't remember. 
 
Q: Did Mr. Simpson ever talk to you about using Mr. Kardashian as an 
attorney? 
 
A: I don't know, to be honest with you. I know they were great friends. I know 
O.J. eventually -- I think his first office was in Bob's building, and -- yeah, 
something like that. 
 
Q: Okay. Do you know if Mr. Simpson ever used Mr. Kardashian in a legal 
capacity? 
 
MR. LEONARD: Objection. Lack of foundation. Calls for speculation. 
 
THE WITNESS: Not that I know of. 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
 
Q: Okay. You don't know of any time Mr. Kardashian provided legal services to 
Mr. Simpson? 
 
A: Not -- 
 
MR. LEONARD: Objection. Same objection. 
 
THE WITNESS: Not that I know of. 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
 
Q: Okay. When did you first meet Skip Taft? 
 
A: I met Skip probably my -- probably in the early '70s. He -- my manager at the 
time was a gentleman by the name of Chuck Barnes, who was the same agent -- 
he was the agent -- O.J. wasthat was his agent, too. Skip and I think Chuck 
had been friends through college. 
 
Q: So when you signed out of college, you used Chuck Barnes as an agent? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: And Simpson had used Chuck Barnes a year before when he signed out of 
college? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Okay. Did you ever -- Strike that. Did Skip Taft ever provide you with legal 
services, ever? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Did you spend much -- Did you meet Mr. Taft through Simpson? 
 
A: I would say I met him through Chuck Barnes when my -- when I became a 
client of Sports -- I think it was Sports Headliners, Incorporated, something like 
that. 
 
Q: Okay. And would you be able to tell me what the relationship was, as you 
understood it, between Skip Taft and Simpson? 
 
MR. LEONARD: Objection. It's vague. Lack of foundation. Calls for 
speculation. 
 
THE WITNESS: At that time I don't know. 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
 
Q: Okay. Do you know whether Mr. Taft was a business advisor of Mr. 
Simpson? 
 
MR. LEONARD: Same objections. 
 
THE WITNESS: I think he was employed by Sports -- I mean by the agency at 
the time. 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
 
Q: That Taft was? 
 
A: I think so. 
 
Q: Okay. Do you know whether he provided any business services to Mr. 
Simpson? 
 
MR. LEONARD: Same objections. 
 
THE WITNESS: I think he was there for Sports Headliners and whoever clients 
they had. I don't know if it was all of us or just certain ones. 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
 
Q: Okay. Do you know whether Mr. Taft ever provided legal services to Mr. 
Simpson? 
 
MR. LEONARD: Same objections. 
 
THE WITNESS: Eventually, when O.J. broke away from Sports Headliners, I 
think Skip at that time became his lawyer in whatever capacity that Skip is 
working for O.J. for. 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
 
Q: Okay. What about Ahmad Rashad, how long have you known him for? 
 
MR. LEONARD: I didn't hear the question. 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
 
Q: Ahmad Rashad, how long have you known him for, first of all? 
 
A: I've been knowing him for quite a long time. We knew of each other through 
college. He was at Oregon while I was at USC. 
 
Q: Okay. And were you friends even in college? 
 
A: No. We started to become friends once I think he got out of Oregon. He had 
moved to Los Angeles. 
 
Q: Okay. And do you know what Rashad's relationship was with Simpson? 
 
A: Friends. 
 
Q: Still friends to this day?  
 
A: Far as I know. 
 
Q: Okay. We had spoken a little bit about Wayne Hughes the other day. Did you 
have any business dealings with Wayne Hughes? 
 
A: Wayne is one of my closest friends. I have been involved with some of -- 
when Wayne first started his company, he got me -- he had me to invest in it. 
 
Q: Public Storage?  
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Okay. And you did invest in it?  
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Okay. Did you work for Public Storage for a number of years? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Okay. And you still talk to Wayne Hughes regularly? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: When was the last time you spoke to him? 
 
A: What's today, Friday? 
 
MR. RE: Uh-huh. 
 
THE WITNESS: Spoke to him Wednesday. 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
 
Q: Did you discuss anything with regard to the deposition that you've -- where 
you've been giving the testimony here today? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Okay. Did he indicate that he knew you were in the middle of your 
deposition testimony when  you 
spoke to him? 
 
A: I guess everybody knows through the leaks in here. Geraldo gets it before 
anybody. 
 
Q: I didn't know anybody knew. 
 
A: Oh, I bet you don't. 
 
Q: When -- Has Mr. Simpson been friends with Wayne Hughes for as long as 
you have, also? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Did Mr. Simpson invest in Public Storage in the same manner you did, if you 
know? 
 
A: That I don't know. 
 
Q: Have Simpson and Hughes been long-time friends? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Do you know whether they still have a strong friendship to this day? 
 
A: As far as I know, yes. 
 
Q: Do you know when the last time Hughes and Simpson have spoken? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Do you know whether they have spoken in the last six months? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Do you know whether Hughes has spoken to Simpson since Simpson's 
release from jail? 
 
A: That I don't know. 
 
Q: Do you know whether Hughes ever visited Simpson in jail? 
 
A: He did. 
 
Q: Do you know whether he visited him more than once? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Do you know in approximately what time frame Mr. Hughes visited Simpson 
in jail after Simpson's initial incarceration? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Did Mr. Hughes ever discuss with you the substance of any conversation he 
had had with Mr. Simpson in jail? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Did Mr. Hughes ever indicate to you that he was going to go speak to Mr. 
Simpson in jail? 
 
A: When you say "speak" -- 
 
Q: Visit him. 
 
A: Oh, yeah, he was going to visit O.J., yes. 
 
Q: Did he tell you he was going to? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Did Mr. Hughes ever tell you what he was going to speak to Mr. Simpson 
about when he visited him? 
 
MR. LEONARD: Objection. 
 
THE WITNESS: No. 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
 
Q: Did Mr. Hughes express -- ever express to you that he was unhappy with 
what was going on in the media with regard to Nicole Brown Simpson? 
 
A: He was very unhappy with all of it. 
 
Q: I am asking you specifically now: Did he indicate to you that he was very 
unhappy with what was going on in the media with regard to Nicole? 
 
MR. LEONARD: Objection. Leading. 
 
THE WITNESS: He didn't say specifically anyone. He was just very upset with 
all of it, the whole picture of it, what the media was doing. 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
 
Q: Did he ever indicate to you that he felt that Mr. Simpson was responsible for 
a lot of the negative media reports that were coming out about Nicole? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Did Mr. Hughes ever indicate to you that he was going to go speak to Mr. 
Simpson about all the negative media that was coming out regarding Nicole? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Did Mr. Hughes ever indicate to you afterwards that he had spoken to Mr. 
Simpson about the negative media coming out about Nicole? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Okay. Did Mr. Hughes ever ask you if you could do anything to control all of 
the negative publicity coming out about Nicole? 
 
A: I wish I could have. No. 
 
Q: Okay. Who is Mark Packer? 
 
A: Mark Packer is a friend that lived on -- lives on the East Coast. 
 
Q: New York? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Okay. And where do you know him from? 
 
A: I met Mark Packer through a friend of mine out here by the name of Alan 
Schwartz. 
 
Q: And Schwartz is from back East also? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: And Schwartz knew Packer before he moved out here to the West Coast? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Okay. Do you know what kind of work Packer does here in the East Coast? 
 
A: I think he's in the restaurant business. He owns a number of restaurants back 
on the East Coast.  
 
Q: When was the last time you spoke to Packer? 
 
A: It's been a while. 
 
Q: Have you spoke to him since Simpson's release? 
 
A: I think I spoke to Packer when I was back on the East Coast working. 
 
Q: Do you know whether he and Mr. Simpson still maintain a relationship -- a 
friendship? 
 
MR. LEONARD: Objection. Lack of foundation. 
 
THE WITNESS: That I don't know. 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
 
Q: Were Simpson and Packer friends at one time? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Okay. Do you know whether they are friends now or not? 
 
MR.LEONARD: Objection. Lack of foundation. 
 
THE WITNESS: As far as I know, yes. 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
 
Q: Okay. How long have you known Cathy Randa? 
 
A: I've known Cathy for a long time. She used to work for Bob Kardashian. 
 
Q: And in what capacity did she work for Kardashian? 
 
A: She was his assistant. 
 
Q: And as an assistant, what type of work did she do for Kardashian? 
 
A: I guess answering phones, type, took dictation, made appointments. 
Whatever assistant's duties are for, she provided. 
 
Q: Do you know what type of work Kardashian was doing that Cathy Randa 
was assisting in? 
 
A: He was a lawyer. 
 
Q: Do you know anything else he did besides lawyering? 
 
A: Him and his brother had started or bought into a newspaper called R & R, 
which is Radio & Records. It's a public -- a news publication that deals with the 
radio stations across the nation. 
 
Q: Did you personally know of anybody who Bob Kardashian provided legal 
services for? 
 
MR. LEONARD: At any time? 
 
THE WITNESS: At any time? 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
 
Q: At any time. 
 
A: He did get into -- briefly he got into representing ballplayers. 
 
Q: Do you know any ballplayer he represented? 
 
A: The names slip me now. This was early on. 
 
Q: Just like that girlfriend in San Francisco in '79? 
 
MR. LEONARD: Object. Argumentative. 
 
THE WITNESS: I answered that question. 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
 
Q: I know. Think you might remember those ballplayers' names later on? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Do you know if he represented them in a agent capacity or a legal capacity? 
 
A: I was -- I -- 
 
MR. LEONARD: I am going to object to that as lack of foundation and asking 
him to speculate. 
 
THE WITNESS: I'd just be guessing. Like I say, I don't know exactly what he 
did for them. 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
 
Q: Other than briefly representing ballplayers, do you know of any legal-related 
work he ever did? 
 
MR. LEONARD: Objection. Lack of foundation. 
 
THE WITNESS: I would be guessing. 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
 
Q: Okay. Going back to Cathy Randa now, how long did she work for Bob 
Kardashian? 
 
A: Long time. I think when Bob -- I don't know if he went full time over to R & 
R or -- whenever he went full time to R &: R, I guess he -- trying to think. That 
would have been... I really don't know. She worked for him for quite a long 
time. 
 
Q: Okay. And do you know where she went to work after she left Kardashian? 
 
A: I think she went to work for O.J. 
 
Q: And did you have a social relationship with Cathy Randa? 
 
A: What do you mean by "social"? 
 
Q: Well, did you ever see her at like parties at Simpson's house? 
 
A: We were friends. I guess she could have been at the house on some events 
that O.J. and Nicole would host. 
 
Q: Would you be able to tell me in what capacity she worked for Simpson? 
 
A: She was O.J.'s assistant. 
 
Q: Do you know what type of work she did for him? 
 
A: She choreographed: She ran his office, made his appointments. 
 
Q: Do you know whether or not she took care of his personal matters also as 
part of her job? 
 
A: When you say -- 
 
MR.LEONARD: Objection. Lack of foundation. Calling for speculation. 
 
THE WITNESS: What do you mean by "personal"? 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
 
