EXAMINATION (Resumed) 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
 
Q: Mr. Cowlings, going back to the morning  of New Year's Day, 1989, okay, 
and the first time you had arrived at Rockingham after the call to Michelle,  you 
indicated that you at one point saw Simpson leave  the kitchen? 
 
MR. LEONARD: I am just going to object because  it mischaracterizes the 
testimony. You said, "the call to Michelle." You meant --  
 
MR. KELLY: From Michelle. I am sorry. 
 
Q: You had gotten a call from Michelle, you  came over to Rockingham, you 
were in the kitchen talking to Nicole, and Mr. Simpson had walked in the  
kitchen at one point. Is that correct? 
 
A: What had happened, while Nicole and I was talking, when I was just standing 
there, I heard some  noise, like just some faint noise, and I walked  towards 
where I heard the noise, and it was from the  kitchen to the dining room. Just as 
I got close to  that door, O.J. was standing there. 
 
Q: And after he was standing there, what, if  anything, did he do? 
 
MR. LEONARD: I am going to object because this  has been asked and 
answered. It was went -- it was gone into in detail. 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
 
Q: You can answer. 
 
A: He wanted to talk to Nicole, and Nicole  didn't want to hear what he wanted 
to talk about. 
 
Q: And then what did Simpson do? 
 
MR. LEONARD: Same objection. 
 
THE WITNESS: She made a motion or she picked , up the phone to dial 911. 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
 
Q: And what did Simpson do then? 
 
A: Something about she going to call the  police again, and he turned around 
and disappeared  back into the darkness. 
 
Q: Did he head toward the back end of the house at that point? 
 
A: Seemed to me, yes. That's -- I didn't  notice him going out -- going around and 
coming out  the front door. I think he went out the back. 
 
Q: Okay. And that was the last time you saw  him before he called you from 
Schwartz's house? 
 
A: I don't know if he called me or Alan  called me. When I saw him later on that 
morning at  Alan's house -- that's the last time I saw him. 
 
Q: But what I am asking you is: The next I time you saw him after you saw him 
leaving toward the back of the house that morning, wasn't it your testimony that 
he then called you from Schwartz's an  hour or two later? 
 
A: I don't know if he called me or Alan  called me, but I did go to Alan's house, 
and that's  where he was. 
 
Q: Okay. When you got there after the call from either Simpson or Schwartz 
that morning, can you tell me exactly what Simpson said to you when you got  
there that morning? 
 
MR. LEONARD: I am going to object. This was  asked at least once before. 
This has been asked and  answered. 
 
MR. KELLY: I will allow you to have a standing objection to every question I 
am going to ask now about New Year's morning of '89. 
 
MR. RE: That doesn't bode well for where we're  going into, I guess. 
 
MR. KELLY: There's not going to be many. 
 
THE WITNESS: He just babbled. He just talked. O.J. has a tendency when he 
talks, he just  goes on and on and on and on. 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
 
Q: Can you tell me specifically what he told you about Alan Schwartz's key and 
the bag of jewelry? 
 
