EXAMINATION BY MR. PETROCELLI: 
 
Q: Mr. Cowlings, my name is Daniel  Petrocelli. I represent Fredric Goldman. 
You have asserted the Fifth Amendment privilege against  self-incrimination a 
number of times throughout this deposition. I would like to ask you some 
questions about that. 
 
Were you aware that your lawyer, Mr. Re,  made comments to the press to the 
effect that you  wanted to talk, you wanted to tell your story? Are you aware of 
that? 
 
MR. RE: Are you asking if he's aware whether  
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Yes. 
 
MR. RE:  I made comments? 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Yes. 
 
Q: Are you aware that your lawyer made  comments on your behalf that you 
wanted to testify fully and completely and wanted to tell the complete story that 
you have? 
 
MR. RE: You talking about with the grant of immunity? 
 
BY MR. PETROCELLI: 
 
Q: Are you aware of that? 
 
A: With the grant of immunity? 
 
Q: Whatever. That you wanted to be able to  tell your story. Yeah, if you had 
immunity, you would  talk. 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Okay. And is that true? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Okay. What have you done to get immunity? 
 
MR. RE: Well, wait a second. He has no obligation to get immunity, he cannot 
get immunity, and under Kauffman and Daly you are the one who can get  him 
immunity. So there is nothing that he can do in  any event.  
 
BY MR. PETROCELLI: 
 
Q: Well, the question is: Have you done  anything, have you taken any effort, 
made any effort  to obtain permission from the D.A.'s office or go to court, seek 
relief, or do anything to enable you to  come here in this case and give full and 
complete  testimony? 
 
MR. LEONARD: Object  
 
MR. RE: There is no procedure for him to do  that. That's an improper question. 
I direct him not  to answer it. 
 
BY MR. PETROCELLI: 
 
Q: Have you instructed your lawyer to take  such actions on your behalf? 
 
MR. RE: He is not a lawyer. He can't instruct  me what to do under the law. It's 
an improper  question. There is nothing that can be done in that  regard, and it's 
totally improper. I direct him.  
 
BY MR. PETROCELLI: 
 
Q: Have you had any discussions with anybody  about whether or not you 
would testify fully and  completely in this deposition in this lawsuit, other  than 
counsel? 
 
A: No. Just with my counsel. 
 
Q: Okay. You understand that the Fifth  Amendment is a right that belongs to 
you and not to your lawyer. Right? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: And it's your choice whether or not to  exercise it. You understand that. 
Right? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: And you can choose not to exercise it and  testify fully and answer all the 
questions. Right? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
