couldn't  tell you what status the y were. 
 
Q: Well, you know he was seeing  Miss Barbieri during his divorce with Nicole, 
right,  back in 1992 when he first met her? 
 
A: Yeah, he was seeing  they were dating. 
 
Q: Right. And did there ever come a time to your knowledge when they stopped 
dating? 
 
A: I really don't know. I really don't. 
 
Q: Did there come a time when you didn't see Paula Barbieri for an extended 
period of time? 
 
A: I wasn't around there a lot. 
 
Q: Okay. How many times have you seen her total in your life before the 
murders? 
 
A: Before the murders? I could probably count it on one hand. 
 
Q: Just about four or five times? 
 
A: If that much. I really didn't see a lot  of Paula and O.J. because I wasn't 
coming around that much. 
 
Q: Okay. So let me make sure we're clear on this. As you sit here today, prior to 
the murders  I am only referring to prior to the murders on  June 12  you 
have no knowledge or information about the status of his relationship with Paula 
Barbieri,  when it was on, when it was off, and so forth? 
 
A: No. No, I don't.   
 
Q: Is that correct?   
 
A: That's correct.   
 
Q: Okay. Do you have any financial  involvement with Mr. Simpson? 
 
MR. LEONARD: Objection.  Vague.  
 
THE WITNESS: No. 
 
BY MR.PETROCELLI: 
 
Q Are you involved in any business ventures with him? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Do you receive any money from him? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Are the two of you invested in any  common businesses or enterprises? 
 
A: There was a  
 
MR. LEONARD: Presently? 
 
MR.PETROCELLI: Yeah. 
 
THE WITNESS: Well, not presently, no. 
 
BY MR. PETROCELLI: 
 
Q: When was the last time? 
 
A: He had called me  that's when he was  involved with Swiss Army knives 
 and he said he  he put my name down as something pertaining to a deal  
that he was involved in. And he said he couldn't go  into details at this point in 
time, but, you know, he  let me know that he was thinking of me, and once it  
was finalized or everything was put in it's proper  place, he would be able to 
explain to me a little more  detail what it was about. 
 
Q: When did that occur? 
 
A: Whenever he was putting together the deal with Swiss Army. 
 
Q: Is that before Nicole's murder? 
 
A: Yes, way before. 
 
Q: Long before? 
 
A: I don't know how long before. 
 
Q: Did that deal ever eventuate? 
 
A: Not that I know of. I never heard any more about it. 
 
Q: So within five years prior to Nicole's death, did you have any common 
business investments  with Mr. Simpson? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Did you receive any money from him other  than a free plane ticket or --  
 
A: No. 
 
Q:  accommodation here or there? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Okay. You supported yourself entirely  
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q:  from your own earnings? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: And, now, did you say you had some kind  of interest in Public Storage? 
 
A: Well, that was years ago. That was when  Public Storage first started. 
 
Q: And you've sold that interest? 
 
A: Yes, long ago. 
 
Q: Okay. And you have no financial interest  in that company anymore? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Or in Louis Marx's company either,  Forschner? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Okay. Has O.J. Simpson transferred any financial investments or instruments 
to you in the last two or three years? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Okay. Do you know whether he has transferred any financial investments or 
instruments to anyone? 
 
MR.LEONARD: Objection. Lack of foundation.  Calling for speculation.   
 
BY MR. PETROCELLI: 
 
Q: Do you know? That's all I'm asking. 
 
A: I don't know. I have no knowledge of  that. 
 
Q: Okay. Do you have any photographs of  O.J. Simpson taken, let's say, within 
five years  before Nicole's death in your possession? 
 
A: I have one. 
 
Q: Just one? 
 
A: Yes. I know for sure I have one. 
 
Q: And where is that? At your house?  
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: And who is in that photograph?  
 
A: O.J. and I. 
 
Q: And when was that taken? 
 
A: It was taken at a football game.  
 
Q: When was that? 
 
A: It was a playoff game.   
 
Q: Years ago? 
 
A: Few years ago. It was  the Raiders  were playing Denver in the playoffs. 
 
Q: Okay. That's the only photograph you have? 
 
A: That I know for sure because I still see it. I mean, I have it up. 
 
Q: Okay. Do you have any other pictures of  Mr. Simpson taken within five 
years before Nicole's  death? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Do you have any notes or letters from  him? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Do you have any notes or letters from  Nicole? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Have you given anybody since Nicole's death copies or originals of any 
photographs? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Or notes or letters?   
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Or documents of any kind? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Okay. Is this deposition the first time you've ever been examined under oath 
concerning the circumstances of Nicole and Ron Goldman's death? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Okay. Has anybody other than Mr. Re ever questioned you about these 
events? 
 
A: I was questioned by two officers the night that I was arrested. 
 
Q: And other than that incident? 
 
MR. RE: You mean questions he has answered,  not people have questioned  
the press have questioned him repeatedly. 
 
MR.PETROCELLI: Not the press. I am talking  about people in their official 
capacity. 
 
THE WITNESS: Well, Don and Vannatter and Lange  
 
BY MR. PETROCELLI: 
 
Q: Okay.  And that's it? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Okay. Have you ever been videotaped in answering questions, practiced, 
rehearsing, anything like that? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Okay. Do you have  what is your educational background?  Did you 
graduate from USC? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Did you ever get a degree? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Have you ever been convicted of a crime? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Have you ever been  of any crime, felony, misdemeanor, anything? 
 
A: Traffic violations. 
 
Q: Prior to working at your current  employer, what did you do for a living? 
 
A: Some film work. I worked as a T.A. on a  number of commercials, worked 
on two features as a  technical adviser on anything related to football. 
 
Q: You retired when? 
 
A: In '79 
 
Q : So from 1979 till your present job, you worked in television? 
 
A: I was involved in advertising; I was involved in a restaurant, worked for 
Public Storage;  done commercial work, film work. 
 
Q: What did you do for Public Storage? 
 
A: I ran their  I came in as a district manager, and then I got appointed to head 
up  start up a maintenance program in maintaining the projects in the Los 
Angeles County area. 
 
Q: And how long did you do that for? 
 
A: I got involved with a restaurant. I started it up, and then the restaurant 
opportunity  came. I was made partners of a restaurant over in Hollywood called 
Fellini's, and then so I left Public  Storage. 
 
Q: You were working full time at Public  Storage? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: And what time period was this? 
 
A: I was there two or three years, I think. 
 
Q: Then you went to Fellini's? 
 
A: Fellini's, yes. 
 
Q: Who was your partner? 
 
A: A guy by the name of Fred Levinson, who was the commercial director who 
I been knowing for a  long time. 
 
Q: And he worked with O.J. Simpson. Right? 
 
A: Yes. Yes, he did. 
 
Q: On the Hertz commercials? 
 
A: I think so. I think so. 
 
Q: And then how long were you involved with  Fellini's? 
 
A: Not too long. I had a problem with two of the other gentlemen that he had 
made partners. 
 
Q: Who were they? 
 
A: One was  I don't know  one was  they were brothers, and one was 
named Alan and I  forgot the other one's name. So we didn't see eye to  eye, so I 
left. 
 
Q: What years did you operate Fellini's? 
 
A: I was only there for about three months,  three or four months. 
 
Q: And what year was that? 
 
A: I wouldn't know. 
 
Q: In the '80s? 
 
A: That was in  yeah, probably in the late '80s, I think. 
 
Q: And after Fellini's, what did you do professionally? 
 
A: What did I do. I think I did commercial work. I did a  trying to think, 
figure out when would this fall in. I was the Kool man, Kool cigarettes print ad, 
black model for Kool for two  years. They had a cigarette campaign.  I did 
billboards, print ads, and I did that for about two years, off and on. 
 
Q: After Fellini's? 
 
A: I don't know where it falls in there. Could have been, or it could have been 
before. I  really couldn't tell you. 
 
Q: And after  what did you do right before  your current job? 
 
A: Couldn't tell you. Probably did  I couldn't tell you. 
 
Q: You don't remember? 
 
A: No, I don't remember. 
 
Q: Okay. What is your wife's name?   
 
A: Marion.   
 
Q: Marion?   
 
A: Marion.  
 
Q: Does she live with you?   
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Where does she reside? 
 
A: She lives on [address deleted]. 
 
Q: Do you know the address? A: I have it written down. 
 
Q: When did you get married? 
 
A: It was July  or was it November. It's been a couple years. I couldn't give 
you the exact date. 
 
Q: What year was it? 
 
A: Probably would have been '93. '93? 
 
Q: Did you have a best man? 
 
A: No, uh-uh. We went to Vegas and got  married. 
 
Q: Okay. Does Mr. Simpson know Marion? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: How long did they know each other? 
 
A: Her and I went together for about a year  almost. He met her, been out with 
her. Nicole, too. 
 
Q: Did Nicole ever meet   
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q:  Marion? 
 
A: I'm sorry. Yes. 
 
Q: And you went out as couples?   
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Okay. How many times did you think that  Nicole and Marion had come into 
contact with each  other? 
 
A: Went by the house once, went to dinner with O.J. and Nicole and two other 
couples. Could  have been two or three times. 
 
Q: Did you and Marion separate before or  after Nicole's death? 
 
A: We just thought that it would have been  best because I wanted to keep her 
out of all this craziness, so I just tried to keep some sanity, you  know, with us. 
It was  just before it happened we kinda like  we were having some 
problems. Then after it happened I just told her, you know, just, you know, be 
best that we just, you know, try to maintain some privacy. 
 
Q: Did she move out of the home you were living in, or did you move out of the 
home? 
 
A: I moved out. 
 
Q: Okay. Did you move out of that home  before or after Nicole's death?   
 
A: Before. 
 
Q: How long before?   
 
A: I don't know. 
 
Q: Days? Weeks? Months? 
 
A: No, it was sometime before. I don't know  when, but I did. 
 
Q: Okay. And what was the address where you  were living in June  on June 
12, 1994? 
 
A: It was on Centinela. 
 
Q: On June 12 of 1994? 
 
A: Oh, June 12th? 
 
Q: Yeah. 
 
A: I was up in the Palisades. 
 
Q: And Marion and you were living on  Centinela? 
 
A: Before then, yes. 
 
Q: You moved out and moved to the Palisades? 
 
A: Yes. I still had my apartment in Santa Monica. 
 
Q: Where does the Santa Monica apartment fit in? I'm a little confused. 
Centinela? 
 
A: No. On San Vicente. 
 
Q: Okay. Let me get this straight. You still had a place on San Vicente in Santa 
Monica while you were living with your wife  
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q:  on Centinela? Is that what you re saying? 
 
A: No. Her and I lived on Centinela, but I still had my apartment on San 
Vicente, 7th and  San Vicente. 
 
Q: And it was vacant? 
 
A: Yeah, there was nobody there. 
 
Q: And then you moved into it? 
 
A: When her and I split up, I went back.  Then when the earthquake hit and 
damaged my apartment, I moved up to the Palisades. 
 
Q: Okay. And that's where you were living on June 12, 1994? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Are you still living there? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: And when did you leave that apartment? 
 
A: Sometime after all the craziness  happened. Could have been a few months 
afterwards. 
 
Q: What was the address of that apartment? 
 
A: Which one? 
 
Q: The one on June 12, 1994, the one where  you were living  
 
A: Up in the Palisades? 
 
Q:  on June 12th. Yeah.   
 
A: It was a house. 
 
Q: Did you own the house? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Did you rent it? 
 
A: Yes, I rented part of the house. 
 
Q: And were you living there with someone? 
 
A: The owner of the house lived in the other part of the house. 
 
Q: What is the name of the owner of the house? 
 
A: (name deleted). 
 
Q: How do you spell the last name?   
 
A: Is it (name deleted)? 
 
Q: Does (name deleted) still live there?  
 
A: Yes. 
 
MR.PETROCELLI: Okay. We will have to break now. I was hoping that we 
could commence again on Monday. Mr. Leonard informs me he is not available 
on  Monday, so I guess we are going to have to schedule this at the next best 
date for everyone. 
 
MR. RE: Tuesday? 
 
MR. LEONARD: I won't be available next week. 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Well, I just want to say on  the record that I would like to 
get this done as soon  as possible. 
 
MR. LEONARD: That's fine. 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: And perhaps you can rearrange  your schedule to make 
yourself available sometime next week? 
 
MR. LEONARD: No, I won't be able to be available next week. 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Okay. Well, when can you make  yourself available? 
 
MR. LEONARD: The week after. 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: On Monday, May 6? 
 
MR. LEONARD: Let me get back to you. I'm  going over  
 
MR. RE: I'll be in trial that week. 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Okay. Well, because of all the objections on the record, I 
just think it's  important that we get this transcript completed as soon as 
possible. 
 
MR. LEONARD: Why don't we keep going now? 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Because I have to stop at  4:30, and I can't finish in a half 
an hour, anyway. 
 
MR. LEONARD: How about tomorrow? 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: And I asked Mr. Re and he is  not available tomorrow, 
although I'm willing to come  in tomorrow to do this. 
 
MR. LEONARD: Well, I am, too, so... 
 
MR. KELLY: I am. 
 
MR. RE: I'm not. 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Okay. So  
 
MR. LEONARD: All right. 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Okay. So I guess we will have  to adjourn at this point. 
 
THE VIDEOGRAPHER: This concludes the deposition of Allen Cowlings, 
Volume III. The number of videotapes used was three. We are going off the 
record, and the time is approximately 4:26. 
 
(ENDING TIME: 4:26 P.M.) 
 
I DECLARE UNDER PENALTY OF PERJURY THAT, THE FOREGOING IS 
TRUE AND CORRECT. 
 
SUBSCRIBED AT ________________, 
 
CALIFORNIA, THIS _ DAY OF _, 19_. 
 
ALLEN COWLINGS 
