<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<P>Cora Fischman concluded her deposition on March 21, 1996, claiming she was unaware of most of the abuse Nicole Brown Simpson said she suffered in her diary. The following is a transcript.</P>
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
<PRE>
SUPERIOR COURT OF THE STATE OF CALIFORNIA   
FOR THE COUNTY OF LOS ANGELES   
   
SHARON RUFO,   
Plaintiff,   
 
v. 
   
ORENTHAL JAMES SIMPSON et al.,    
Defendants   
   
FREDRIC GOLDMAN, etc., et al.,   
Plaintiffs,   
   
vs.   
   
ORENTHAL JAMES SIMPSON, et al.,   
Defendants   
   
LOUIS H. BROWN, etc.,   
Plaintiffs,   
   
vs.   
   
ORENTHAL JAMES SIMPSON,   
Defendant.   
   
 
Videotaped deposition of CORA A. FISCHMAN, taken on behalf 
of the Plaintiffs, at 11377 West Olympic Boulevard, 10th Floor, 
Los  Angeles, California, commencing at 10:42 a.m., on 
Thursday, March 21, 1996, before David S. Coleman, CSR 
#4613, pursuant to Subpoena. 
   
APPEARANCES:   
FOR THE PLAINTIFFS FREDRIC GOLDMAN, ET AL:   
MITCHELL, SILBERBERG & KNUPP   
BY: DANIEL M. PETROCELLI, ESQ.   
11377 West Olympic Boulevard   
Sixth Floor   
Los Angeles, California 90064-1683   
  
FOR THE PLAINTIFF ESTATE OF BROWN:   
JOHN QUINLAN KELLY, ESQ.   
330 Madison Avenue   
New York, New York 10017-5090   
(212) 682-1700   
  
-and-  
  
NATASHA ROIT, ESQ.  
116 North Robertson Boulevard  
Suite 705  
Los Angeles, California 90048  
  
FOR THE PLAINTIFF SHARON RUFO   
HORNBERGER & CRISWELL   
BY: MICHAEL A. BREWER, ESQ.   
444 South Flower Street   
Third-First Floor   
Los Angeles, California 90071   
   
FOR THE DEFENDANT ORENTHAL JAMES SIMPSON:   
BAKER, SILBERBERG & KEENER   
BY: PHILLIP A. BAKER 
2850 Ocean Park Boulevard   
Suite 300   
Santa Monica, California 90405-2936   
   
FOR THE WITNESS:   
KRAMER & McSHANE 
PHILIP A. KRAMER, ESQ.  
12100 Wilshire Boulevard 
Suite 850 
Los Angeles, California 90405  
  
ALSO PRESENT: ORENTHAL JAMES SIMPSON 
  
WITNESS:  
  
CORA A. FISCHMAN - VOLUME 3  
Examination by Mr. Kelly 650, 800 
Examination by Mr. Petrocelli 714  
Examination by Mr. Baker 784 
 
UNANSWERED QUESTIONS:  
(None)  
EXHIBITS:  
Plaintiffs' Description Identified  
165 Transcript of Interview with Barbara Walters of Cora 
Fischman 
 
 
THE VIDEOGRAPHER: Good morning. Here begins videotape 
No. 1 in the deposition of Cora A. Fischman, Volume III, in the 
consolidated cases of Fredric Goldman, Sharon Rufo and Louis 
Brown vs. Orenthal James Simpson in the Superior Court, State of 
California, County of Los Angeles, the lead case number of which 
is SC 031947. 
 
Today's date is Thursday, March 21st, 1996.  The time is 
approximately 10:42.  This deposition is being taken at 11377 
West Olympic Boulevard in Los Angeles, California, and was 
made at the request of plaintiff of the Law Offices of Mitchell, 
Silberberg & Knupp. 
 
The videographer is Rod Rigole, employed by Coleman, Haas, 
Martin & Schwab of Los Angeles, California. 
 
Would counsel please identify yourselves and state whom you 
represent. 
 
MR. KELLY: John Kelly for Plaintiff Brown. 
 
MR. PETROCELLI: Daniel Petrocelli for Plaintiff Fredric 
Goldman. 
 
MS. ROIT: Natasha Roit for Plaintiff Brown. 
 
MR.BAKER: Phil Baker for O.J. Simpson. 
 
MR. KRAMER: Philip Kramer for the witness. 
 
CORA A. FISCHMAN, having been previously sworn, was 
examined and testified further as follows: 
 
EXAMINATION (Resumed) BY MR. KELLY: 
 
Q: Good morning, Miss Fischman. 
 
A: Good morning. 
 
Q: Between yesterday when we finished and this morning, have 
you spoken to anybody about your testimony except for your 
attorney, Mr. Kramer? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: And who was that? 
 
A: I talked to my kids. 
 
Q: Okay.  Anybody other than your children? 
 
A: I talked to Ron and I talk about how my kids are doing. 
 
Q: Okay.  All right.  But nothing about your testimony 
specifically? 
 
A: No, not specifically. 
 
Q: Okay.  Yesterday we had talked a little bit about an incident in 
late May where you had picked up Nicole's children one morning 
for school and Mr. Simpson had subsequently shown up, and the 
children went from your car into his.  Is that correct? 
 
A: Right. 
 
Q: Okay.  And what street was that on again? 
 
A: We were on San Vicente Boulevard. 
 
Q: Okay.  And I believe you indicated that Mr. Simpson pulled in 
front of your car? 
 
A: No.  Behind my car. 
 
Q: Okay.  He pulled behind your car. 
 
A: Right. 
     
Q: And Sydney and Justin got out of your car and got into his? 
     
A: Right. 
  
Q: Okay.  And did he pull out in front of you then after they got 
into his car? 
     
A: Yes. 
     
Q: Okay.  And after he pulled out in front of you, did you proceed 
directly to the school then? 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Okay.  You didn't stop anywhere? 
 
A: No. 
 
Q: Okay.  When was the last time that morning that you saw Mr. 
Simpson and the children then? 
 
A: When was the last time? 
 
Q: Yeah. 
 
A: That was the last time.  I didn't see them after that. 
 
Q: Okay.  When you pulled up to the school, you didn't see him 
there in the Bentley? 
 
A: No.  I didn't notice. 
     
Q: Okay. In fact after he left that intersection there, you didn't see 
the car again, did you? 
 
A: No, I didn't see the car. 
 
MR. BAKER: Leading. 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
 
Q: Okay.  And it's your testimony that after that incident, later that 
day or at any time you never discussed it with Nicole? 
 
A: Later? 
 
Q: Yeah. 
 
A: Yes. 
     
Q: Okay.  You did discuss it with her. 
 
A: I did discuss it, yeah.  I called her on the phone.  I said what 
was going on. 
 
Q: And that was after the kids left the car? 
     
A: Yes. 
     
Q:: Okay.  And what did she tell you? 
 
A: She said that O.J. was mad. 
 
Q: Okay.  
     
A: And that O.J.'s mad at me.  I said, "Why? What did I do?"  She 
said well, he's just mad at me.  So that's what. 
 
Q: After that phone conversation did you have any other 
conversations with Nicole? 
 
A: That was it. 
 
Q: That was it? 
 
A: Yeah. 
 
Q: Okay.  And you have no knowledge of Mr. Simpson going 
back to Bundy with the children after they got into his car? 
 
A: No. 
  
MR. BAKER: Asked and answered. 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
 
Q: On June 14th, 1994, okay, this is two days after the murder 
now, do you recall where you were that day? 
 
A: What's June 14th? 
 
Q: It's Tuesday. 
 
A: Tuesday? 
 
Q: Yeah. 
 
A: Tuesday. I was at home. 
 
Q: Okay.  Do you recall going to Bundy at all? 
     
A: Tuesday.  Yes, I did go to Bundy. 
  
Q: Okay.  Do you recall approximately what time that was that 
you went over to Bundy, Nicole's condo? 
     
A: I went in the afternoon. 
     
Q: Okay.  And do you recall what caused you to go over there? 
     
A: Lou asked me for the key to the Bundy house. 
     
Q: Okay.  Lou had called you? 
 
A: Lou went to Rockingham. 
 
Q: To your place on Rockingham? 
 
A: Right, in the morning, and asked where Alvia was. 
  
Q: Okay.  Was Alvia there at that time? 
     
A: Yes, yes, Alvia was there, right. 
 
Q: Okay. And did Alvia talk to Lou at that point? 
     
A: No, I don't think so, no. 
 
Q: Did she leave with Lou? 
A: She was -- Alvia was at home, at my house at Rockingham. 
 
Q: At your place. 
 
A: Yeah, at my -- at Rockingham. 
 
Q: What I am asking you is: When Lou came and spoke to her, 
did she then go with Lou back to Bundy? 
     
A: I think so, yes. 
  
Q: Okay.  And did you speak to Lou at that time? 
     
A: Yes. 
     
Q: Did you give him the keys to Bundy? 
     
A: No, I didn't give my keys to -- he asked for Alvia's keys at that 
time. 
 
Q: Did Alvia have a set of keys to Bundy? 
     
A: Yes. 
  
Q:: And did Alvia give Lou a set of keys? 
 
A: I don't know.  I think so.  I'm not sure. 
     
Q: Okay.  Well, do you know how Lou ended up getting into the 
Bundy residence that morning? 
 
MR. BAKER: Speculation. 
 
THE WITNESS: I don't know. 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
     
Q: Okay.  Did you let him in? 
       
A: No, I didn't let him in. 
  
Q: Okay.  When did you have occasion to go over to Bundy 
yourself? 
 
A: An occasion? 
     
Q: That day.  Sorry. 
       
A: That day? 
 
Q: That day. 
 
A: I went in the afternoon, because they asked me to help take the 
stuff out. 
     
Q: Who had asked you to take the stuff out? 
     
A: No.  You know what?  I think I drove Alvia to Bundy.  That's 
why I went there. 
     
Q: That morning or that afternoon? 
 
A: Afternoon. 
     
Q: And when you got there, who else was at Bundy at that time? 
 
A: The Browns, Denise and Tanya. 
 
Q: Was Dominique there? 
     
A: Dominique?  I'm not sure. 
     
Q: And was Lou Brown there? 
 
A: Who? 
 
Q: Lou Brown. 
 
A: Lou?  I think he was there. 
     
Q: Okay. Anybody else, if you recall? 
 
A: A.C. was there. 
     
Q: Okay.  Anybody else? 
       
A: That's it. 
     
Q: Was Ron Fischman there? 
 
A: No, Ron wasn't there. 
     
Q: Was A.C. already there when you got to 875 Bundy? 
     
A: Yes, he was there already. 
  
Q: And what, if anything, was A.C. doing when you got there? 
     
A: We were putting all of Nicole's belongings to the car.  That 
was pretty much what we were doing. 
     
Q: But did you pack anything yourself? 
     
A: Yeah, I went upstairs and put everything in bags. 
     
Q: And did you have any conversations with A.C. that day? 
     
A: Yeah. We just said, you know -- he told me, "Just be strong.  
Be strong."  That's pretty much what he told me. 
     
Q: Okay.  Did he say anything about Mr. Simpson at all? 
     
A: No. 
     
Q: Did you have any discussions with him as to how the murders 
had occurred? 
       
A: No. 
       
Q:: No discussion about who might have done it? 
     
A: No. 
     
Q: Did A.C. tell you he had spoken to Simpson? 
 
A: No. 
  
Q: That never even came up? 
     
A: No. 
     
Q: Did you remove anything from Bundy yourself? 
     
   
MR. KRAMER: Do you understand the question? 
     
You're asking -- 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
     
Q: Yeah, and kept it.  I'm sorry. 
 
A: No. 
     
Q:: You didn't keep any of Nicole's belongings -- 
 
A: No. 
     
Q: -- from Bundy? 
 
A: No. 
  
Q: Was there any other time when you were over at Bundy that 
week later in the week? 
     
A: That was the last time. 
 
Q: Okay. Did you go there on the 17th?  
 
A: What's the 17th? You have to give me -- 
     
Q: That was the day after the funeral, the day of the Bronco chase. 
     
A: Yes, I went back, yes. 
     
Q: Okay. And did someone call you to come over? 
     
A: I was so confused that day.  I think Lou. 
     
Q: I'm sorry. I'll come back to the 17th.  On the 14th was there a 
time that Simpson called the Bundy residence when you were 
there? 
     
MR. KRAMER: This is the Tuesday when they were packing? 
     
BY MR. KELLY: 
     
Q: Yeah, Tuesday on the 14th, when you were packing. 
     
A: I don't know, you know, because I was upstairs in the 
bedroom, so... 
     
Q: Okay.  Was Ron Hardy there that day? 
 
A: Yes, he was there. 
 
Q: He was. 
 
A: Uh-huh. 
 
Q: Did you see him on the telephone at all? 
     
A: I was upstairs, so I wouldn't know, so... 
     
Q: Okay.  And as far as you know, Ron Fischman wasn't there at 
all on the 14th? 
     
A: Ron wasn't there, no. 
     
W: Okay.  Was he there on the 17th at all? 
 
A: 17th? 
 
Q: Yeah, the day after the funeral, was he at Bundy? 
     
A: Yeah, he followed me, yes, yeah. 
 
Q: Did you and he discuss him coming over to Bundy or if he 
would come over there? 
     
A: At the time, no, I don't think so.  I just heard over the news that 
someone was at Bundy, and then when I -- Lou called, or I must 
have spoken to someone at the time.  He said that there was 
another 911 or Lou called 911.  So I panicked.  I said, "Oh, my 
God, something happened again." And  that was -- you know, like 
I got scared.  I said, "Another one?"  So my instinct was just to go 
there again and find out. 
 
Q: Okay.  Did you have any discussions with your husband before 
you went over there? 
     
A: I don't remember. I mean, it was like -- the whole thing was -- 
to me was -- I was very confused and... 
 
Q: Did you have any discussions between the 14th and the 17th 
with your husband about who might be responsible for Nicole's 
murder? 
       
MR. BAKER: Leading. 
     
THE WITNESS: At that time? 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
     
Q: Yeah. 
 
A: We talked, but it was hush-hush.  We were like we didn't 
know.  It was like we were afraid to talk because we were afraid 
who really did it, afraid that we might get hurt. 
     
Q: Well, who did he tell you he thought did it? 
     
A: At that time our first initial reaction was he did it, you know. 
     
Q: Simpson did it? 
 
A: That's what we thought. 
    
Q: Okay.  That was your husband's reaction, too? 
 
MR. BAKER: Speculation. 
     
THE WITNESS: At that time, yes. 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
     
Q: Okay. Did your husband have another theory also in the days 
following the murder as to who might have committed it? 
     
A: I don't know. 
     
Q: He didn't talk to you about anybody other than Simpson being 
the possible murderer? 
  
A: No. 
     
Q: Did he relate to you any conversations he had had with A.C.? 
       
A: I don't know about that. 
     
Q: Okay. Did you have any conversations after the 14th with 
A.C., either at the wake or funeral? 
     
MR. KRAMER: The 14th is the Tuesday? 
     
MR. KELLY: Yeah. 
     
THE WITNESS: Yeah. 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
     
Q:: Okay. And did you speak to him at the wake? 
     
A: No. 
 
Q: Did you speak to him at the funeral? 
     
A: No. 
     
Q: When did you next speak to him? 
       
A: You mean to A.C.  Right? 
     
Q: Yeah. 
     
A: That walk that I did with him on San Vicente. 
     
Q: Okay. And that was later in June after -- 
 
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Okay.  And he had called you? 
       
A: Yes. 
     
Q: Okay. And what had he said to you when he called you? 
     
A: He said -- he asked how I was and how I'm doing, and he said, 
"Would you like to talk?"  I said yes, you know, and that was it.  
So he said, "We'll meet at a coffee shop."  
 
Q: Okay.  And how long did you talk to him for? 
     
A: I would say less than half an hour.  15, 20 minutes.  We walked 
down San Vicente. 
     
Q: And did A.C. indicate to you that he had spoken to Simpson at 
all prior to your meeting? 
     
A: No. 
     
Q: Okay. Did he tell you anything that Simpson had said to him 
about the murders? 
     
A: He didn't say anything about that. 
 
Q: Okay.  He didn't talk to you at all about who might have 
committed the murders other than Simpson? 
     
A: No, he didn't say anything. 
     
Q: Did he in any way indicate to you that he thought Simpson had 
committed the murders? 
     
A: At that time --  
     
MR. BAKER: I think this has been asked and answered. 
     
THE WITNESS: I don't remember anymore, no. 
     
BY MR. KELLY: 
 
Q: Nothing? 
     
A: I don't think so, no. 
     
Q: Did he talk about Nicole's relationship with Simpson at all? 
     
A: Yeah, we talked about that, yeah. 
     
Q: Okay.  Do you recall what he said? 
       
A: He said they had a very passionate relationship, that Nicole 
was a very devoted wife. 
     
Q: And what did he say about Simpson? 
     
A: And that both of them just -- were just -- they loved each other. 
     
Q: Okay.  Did he indicate that there was a problem also or -- 
     
A: Oh, yeah, he mentioned about O.J.'s womanizing. 
     
Q: Okay. Anything else? 
       
A: That was it. 
     
Q: Did he mention 1989 at all, the New Year's Day incident? 
     
A: No, he didn't mention that, no. 
     
Q: Okay.  And after that conversation with A.C., have you spoken 
to him since at all about this? 
     
A: I'm sorry.  Did I talk to who? 
     
Q: A.C. at all after this one conversation this day. 
     
MR. KRAMER: You're asking any conversation -- 
     
MR. KELLY: Any time. 
 
MR.KRAMER: -- in the last two years? 
     
MR. KELLY: Any time. 
     
THE WITNESS: Well, he was at the house at Rockingham when I 
picked up the kids one time. I said hello, and he asked me how I 
was doing.  That was it.  And I asked him -- he said he's working.  
I said, "Oh, that's good."  That's pretty much -- 
     
BY MR. KELLY: 
     
Q: Okay.  You didn't discuss the case at all? 
     
A: No. 
     
Q: Simpson? 
       
A: No. 
 
MR. BAKER: Asked and answered. 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
 
Q: Now, I want to ask you about the incident at Tryst, the 
restaurant. 
     
A: Yes. 
     
Q: Okay.  You were there that night. 
       
A: Yes. 
     
Q: Okay.  And you were at a table with a number of other people? 
     
A: Yes. 
     
Q: And who else was there, if you recall? 
     
A: Cynthia was there. 
     
Q: Okay. 
     
A: [Name Deleted].  [Name Deleted].  One guy that Nicole was 
trying to set up with Cici, so I forgot the name. 
     
Q: Was Keith there also or... 
     
A: Keith was there, but he didn't sit with us. You know, he was 
just there. 
     
Q: Okay. And did there come a time that Simpson showed up 
there? 
     
A: Yeah.  We were waiting for a table.  Then he showed up, so... 
     
Q: And did you eventually get a table? 
     
A: We waited -- we waited quite a bit. 
 
Q: Okay.  Did there come a time that night that you left before the 
others? 
       
MR. BAKER: Leading. 
     
THE WITNESS: We left? What do you mean? 
     
BY MR. KELLY: 
     
Q: That you left before the other people -- 
       
A: With Nicole? 
 
Q: -- you were with. 
       
A: No.  We ate dinner there, so 
 
Q: And who had you gone there with? 
 
A: Who did I go? 
     
Q: No.  Who had you gone to the restaurant with? 
     
A: I went with Nicole -- actually, no.  I went myself.  We went 
separate cars. 
       
Q: Okay. 
 
A: She was with [Name Deleted]at the time. 
 
Q: Okay. And you arrived there yourself in your own car? 
     
A: Yes.  Yes. 
     
Q: And did you leave by yourself? 
       
A: Yes. 
     
Q: Did you leave before the check had come, or everybody left at 
the same time? 
 
A: We pretty much left at the same time. 
     
Q: You didn't leave before the others? 
     
MR. BAKER: Asked and answered. 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
 
Q: Miss Fischman, did you leave before the others? 
     
MR. BAKER: Asked and answered. 
     
THE WITNESS: Nicole and [Name Deleted]were there while -- 
we pretty much left the same time. 
       
BY MR. KELLY: 
       
Q: Okay.  You didn't express any discomfort about being there 
and left before dinner was finished? 
 
A: Oh, no. We finished dinner and everything.  We ate, and then, 
you know, finished -- we ate and then we left, and that was it. 
     
Q: Okay. 
     
MR. KRAMER: Just do the best you can. 
     
BY MR. KELLY: 
Q: Do the best you can. 
      
MR. KRAMER: Do the best you can. 
      
THE WITNESS: Exactly, but you're trying to say what -- 
       
MR. KRAMER: No, don't analyze it.  Just listen -- 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
 
Q: Don't wonder what I'm asking.  Okay? 
 
A: Okay. 
 
MR. KRAMER: Just think about it -- 
      
THE WITNESS: I am. 
 
