me to jail," you don't remember anything else she said to you? 
 
A: Actually that's what she said: "That   guy's trying to send me to 
jail," you know. 
     
Q: Okay.  How long was Nicole sick with double pneumonia?  Do 
you remember approximately how long that was? 
     
A: Oh, she was actually -- she couldn't run for a week, so we ran 
and then it got worse, her coughing got worse, and that was it.  
She was... 
     
Q: Okay.  And I believe you indicated you had never seen 
Simpson over at the house during that week she was sick? 
     
A: No. 
     
Q: Okay.  Did you talk to her everyday? 
     
A: Yes. 
     
Q: Okay. Did she ever indicate to you that Simpson had been over 
to the house that week while she was sick? 
     
A: Not really, no. I mean, she mentioned about the flowers and 
the chicken soup, you know.  Chicken soup, yeah. 
     
Q: That was just one day, wasn't it? 
     
A: I don't remember.  No, I don't remember. 
 
Q: Okay.  Do you know who was up there taking care of Nicole, if 
anybody was? 
 
A: Alvia was there. 
     
Q: Okay. Do you know whether her mom was up there at all? 
     
A: No, I don't think so. I don't know. 
 
Q: Okay.  Your kids would usually -- I mean, you said they spent 
an awful lot of time with the Simpson kids, didn't they? 
     
A: Yes. 
     
Q: Okay. And when you would take your daughter, your 12-year-
old daughter, 11-year-old daughter, somewhere, to an amusement 
park or something, would she usually take Sydney with her also? 
       
A: Yes. 
     
Q: Okay. Or if Sydney was going somewhere, would she usually 
take your daughter with her, too? 
     
A: Yes. 
     
Q: Was that always the case? 
 
A: Yes. 
     
Q: Inseparable. 
      
A: Yes. 
     
Q: Okay. 
     
A: The four of them were inseparable. 
     
Q: Okay. As of June 12th, 1994, do you know whether your 
daughter had any plans of going anywhere with Sydney? 
     
A: What's June 12? 
     
Q: That was the day of the murders. 
       
A: No, we didn't have any plans, no. 
       
Q: Okay. There was no discussion of your kids and the Simpson 
kids -- 
     
A: No. 
     
Q: -- in the near future going anywhere? 
     
A: No. 
     
Q: Okay.  All right.  Do you keep a calendar book, by the way? 
     
A: No. 
 
Q: Ever keep a calendar book? 
      
A: I used to. 
     
Q: In '94 did you keep a calendar book? 
     
A: No. 
     
Q: Okay. With the recital, we're talking June 12th now, how long 
was that entire recital from start to finish? 
     
A: It was an hour.  Oh, you mean from when we sat there till -- 
     
Q: Yeah, till the bitter end. 
       
A: Oh, my God, till... 
     
Q: It wasn't as long as the deposition, was it? 
     
A: It seemed that -- I think it was -- 
 
Q: It was a long one, wasn't it?  Weren't there 30 -- some acts?  Do 
you recall? 
     
A: Oh, yeah, and it so happened that the -- 
 
MR. BAKER: I think this is leading. 
     
MR. KELLY: It's not.  I'm refreshing her memory. 
     
THE WITNESS: I think she was the last act. 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
     
Q: Could you approximate the length of time you were at the 
recital from the time you arrived there till the time you left? 
     
A: Two hours. 
     
Q: Do you recall how long after you arrived there that Mr. 
Simpson arrived there? 
     
A: He arrived in middle of the program, so I would say an hour. 
     
Q: And you indicated that he sat near Nicole? 
       
A: Yes. The same row with Nicole. 
     
Q: And how many seats were empty between them? 
     
       
MR. BAKER: Asked and answered. 
     
THE WITNESS: About three, three seats. 
     
BY MR. KELLY: 
     
Q: And were you sitting in front of them or behind them? 
     
A: I was sitting in front of them. No.  I was -- they were behind 
me, yeah, in front of them. 
     
Q: Okay. Did you turn around to talk to Nicole at all during the 
recital? 
     
A: About any specific? 
 
Q: Just in general. 
 
A: Yeah, we did, yes. 
     
Q: Okay. And were your kids back with the Simpson kids in 
between? 
     
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Okay. Did you ever during that hour period or more ever see 
O.J. Simpson talk to Nicole Simpson? 
     
A: No. 
    
Q: Did you ever see them looking at each other, even? 
     
A: I was behind them, so -- 
 
Q: You were in front of them. 
 
A: Yeah, I was in front of them, right. 
 
Q: Okay.  There was an intermission during this recital, wasn't 
there? 
     
A: Yes. 
     
Q: Okay.  Do you recall seeing either Mr. Simpson or Nicole 
standing up during the intermission? 
     
A: No. 
     
Q: They both stayed in their seats? 
     
A: See, O.J. left sometime during the program, and then when he 
got back, he was sitting at the corner and he was holding flowers. 
     
Q: So how long was he there before he left? 
     
A: How long? 
 
Q: Yeah. 
     
A: I don't know. I mean, I wasn't paying attention. 
     
Q: Okay.  When you say he was seated in a "corner," he was by 
himself, wasn't he? 
     
A: Yes. Because the kids were all in back already, the whole -- at 
the time. 
     
Q: Okay.  And he grabbed the second -- separate chair and was 
seated in the corner of the gym? 
     
A: Right, yes. 
     
Q: Okay.  And how long was he seated there for? 
     
A: How long? 
     
Q: Yeah. 
     
A: I don't remember.  I don't know. 
     
Q: Okay. Well, the last act -- 
     
A: 5 minutes, 10 minutes, 20 minutes. 
     
Q: Well, the last act was your daughter and Sydney, was it not? 
     
A: I would say 10 minutes. 
     
Q: Yeah.  The last act had your daughter and Sydney in it? 
     
A: Yeah. 
 
Q: Okay. And at that point he was seated back in the corner on the 
separate chair? 
     
A: Yes. 
     
Q: Okay. And was that the only act that Sydney was in during the 
recital, was the last act? 
     
A: Yes. 
     
Q: So when Sydney performed, Mr. Simpson was sitting in the 
back of the auditorium in a separate chair, and Nicole was in her 
regular seat that she had been in for the whole recital.  Is that 
correct also? 
     
A: At that time we were all standing up. We were all excited, so I 
didn't even notice that.  Because we were all standing up because 
we were so excited about the program, so I don't know.  It was -- 
the whole thing was like -- 
     
Q: Okay. Well, did- 
     
A: I don't remember. I don't remember. 
     
Q: Do you remember where Simpson was at that time? 
     
A: Well, the last time I saw him, he was at the corner, so that was 
the last time I saw him. 
     
Q: You didn't see him move up again, did you? 
     
A: No. 
     
Q: Okay. And the last time you saw Nicole, she was still in that 
row of seats where the kids were also? 
     
A: They were all together already because we were all standing 
up.  We were all -- 
     
Q: Including Nicole. 
       
A: Yeah.  Yes.  Yes. 
     
Q: And Mr. Simpson was separate from all of you. 
 
A: He was not with us, yes. 
     
Q: And that's all I'm asking. He was separate, back in the corner. 
     
A: Exactly, right. 
     
Q: And you and Nicole and the Brown family and everybody was 
together. 
     
A: We were all -- yes. 
     
Q: Okay. And you didn't talk to Simpson at all that day at the 
recital. 
     
A: No. I said, "You look tired." 
     
Q: And where was he seated when you said that? 
     
A: I just look in the back and I says, you know, "You look tired." 
     
Q: Yeah. That was in the row of chairs there? 
     
A: Yes, yes, when he just walked in. 
 
Q: And you didn't talk to him after that at all? 
     
A: No more. 
     
Q: Did you see who he spoke to, if anybody, during the recital? 
       
A: No. 
     
Q: Your husband was at the recital, wasn't he? 
     
A: Yes. 
     
Q: Did you see him speaking to your husband at all? 
     
A: Well, I asked Ron to take pictures you know.  He says, "Why 
don't we all take pictures," stuff like that, so that was --yeah. 
     
Q: That was after the recital. 
 
A: That was during the recital. That was, you know, while we 
were waiting for the program, you know, when Sydney was there 
and [Name Deleted], I said, "Take pictures," so -- 
     
Q: But that wasn't him talking to Simpson at all, was it? 
     
A: No. No. 
     
Q: It had nothing to do with Simpson. 
     
A: No. 
     
Q: Okay.  My question to you is: Did you ever see your husband 
talking to Simpson at all either during or after the recital? 
     
A: I didn't see him, no. 
     
Q: Okay.  Did you see Simpson talking to anybody either during 
or after the recital? 
     
A: I saw a few people saying hello, yeah. 
     
Q: Okay. Other than that? 
       
A: No. 
     
Q: Nicole had a camera at the recital, didn't she? 
     
A: I'm sorry.  What? 
     
Q: Did Nicole have a camera at the recital? 
     
A: I don't remember. Yes, I think so.  Or a video.  I'm not sure. 
     
Q: Okay.  She had some sort of camera, though. 
     
A: Yeah, right. 
     
Q: And why did you ask your husband to take a picture of 
Simpson with Sydney? 
     
MR. BAKER: Asked and answered. 
     
THE WITNESS: I don't know.  I mean, to me I thought it was 
cute, that they had that nice outfit, you know. 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
     
Q: Okay.  Were you under the impression that Nicole wouldn't be 
taking a picture of Sydney with her father? 
 
MR. BAKER: Leading. 
     
THE WITNESS: No, I was not even thinking about that. No. 
 
BY MR. KELLY: 
     
Q: Let me ask you:  You've said you've had long conversations 
with Simpson since his release from jail, didn't you? 
 
MR. BAKER: Misstates her testimony. 
 
THE WITNESS: Long conversations? 
     
BY MR. KELLY: 
     
Q: Well, conversations with him. 
       
A: Yes. 
     
Q: Okay. And that's been over at Rockingham? 
     
A: Yes. 
 
Q: Okay.  Could you tell me the first time you were over there and 
spoke to him after his release? 
 
A: The first time? 
 
Q: Yeah. 
 
MR. BAKER: I think this has been covered. 
 
MR. KELLY: It hasn't. 
     
THE WITNESS: I -- the first time was I asked where the kids 
were, so I -- Gigi called me -- oh, no.  Actually I called, you know, 
the housekeeper.  I asked if he's here.  And so I said I would like 
to see him.  That was it. 
     
BY MR. KELLY: 
 
Q: And -- 
 
A: And so I went there, and that's pretty much -- you know, I 
asked how he was doing, "How are the kids?  Did you see the 
kids?" and that's what we did. 
     
Q: Okay.  Did you talk about the trial at all? 
     
A: No. 
     
Q: Did you talk about Nicole at all? 
     
A: We talked about Nicole.  I -- you know, I kinda said -- you 
know, we commiserated, you know.  We were both crying. 
     
Q: Did he indicate to you what his plans were now that he was 
out? 
     
A: At that time he said that he's -- "They're investigating.  They're 
gonna look for the real killers." 
     
Q: Who did he say was investigating? 
     
A: He said he's hired investigators, so... 
       
Q: He said he had hired them? 
     
A: Well, he said there are private investigators there and they're 
looking, so... 
     
Q: Did he say these were people that he had hired? 
     
A: I don't know.  I didn't go into specific. 
     
